Thus the engagement entered into iu Justinian’s time by a defendant who appeared in person covered the ground oi both (1) the old vadimonium or cautio iudicio sisti, Gaius iv. 185, which secured tbe appearance of the defendant in iure in cases of adjoumment‚ and (2) the clause de re defendenda ol the security iudicatum solvi ; it bound him to appear io court on the day of trial and defend the action: but be was no longer required to guarantee satisfaction oi the judgment. The ordinary mode of entering into this engagement was satisdatio 3 but even before the time of Gaius the praetor had drawn distinctions in vadimonia, being satisfied in some cases with a merely personal undertaking without sureties (vadimonium purum), and in others with such undertaking sortified by the oath or bya summary process ior the recovery ol the recognisance (⁴recuperatoribus suppositis’Gaius iv. 185). Under Justinian landowners (Dig, 2. 8. 15) and personae illustres (Cod. 12. 1. 17) could be compelled to bind themselves in iudicio permanere usquead terminum litis only by a written cautio iuratoria ; it is not clear who were privileged to give a bare promise to this effect, though the edict seems to have con· tained earesul regulations on the subject, Gaius loc cin: ‘pro tenore generalium edictorum’ Cod. 12. 22. 8.
